article.description:
Shaquille O'Neal scored 35 points on 14-of-18 shooting, and the Los Angeles Lakers defeated the slumping Toronto
Raptors 104-88 Sunday night for their second straight victory.
article.headline: Lakers blow out Raptors for second straight win
article.linkText: This time, Lakers leave no doubt in beating Raptors
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Two blowout victories might be what helps cure the ailing Los Angeles Lakers. Shaquille O'Neal scored 35 points on 14-of-18 shooting, and the Lakers defeated the slumping Toronto Raptors 104-88 Sunday night for their second straight victory. "It definitely feels good to get a couple wins going into the end of the year,'' guard Derek Fisher said. "We're coming around.'' The three-time champion Lakers still ended the year in unfamiliar territory with a losing record (13-19) for the first time since 1993. But equaling their longest winning streak of the season gave them hope of turning things around in the new year. They are off until Saturday, when they play at Phoenix. "Regardless of our opponent, it's something we feel we can build on,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. Kobe Bryant, playing with a slightly sprained right wrist that he said was stiff, had 13 points and 12 assists one night after scoring 39 against the Nuggets. In that game, the Lakers shot a season-high 58 percent and they stayed close to that mark against Toronto by hitting 53 percent. "This is very encouraging for us to come out and have two back-to-back blowouts,'' Bryant said. "We're moving in the right direction. We took a couple steps forward these last two games.'' Morris Peterson scored 18 points for Toronto, which lost its season-high sixth straight and 12th in 14 games. Although the Lakers' consecutive victories have been against two of the NBA's worst teams -- Denver and Toronto -- they took a step on the road to respectability by showing a killer instinct missing most of the season. When the Raptors pulled within nine points in the third quarter, Bryant made two free throws and then scored on a flashy driving layup in which he did a 180-degree turn. Slava Medvedenko got fouled on a fastbreak layup and made the free throw to give the Lakers an 80-65 lead heading into the final quarter. "You can feel the momentum building, our rhythm getting better and better with each game,'' Bryant said. "It was just a matter of busting through the door and have the feeling that we could step on the gas at will. That's what we're looking for.'' The Raptors didn't make a run in the fourth, when O'Neal scored seven points in a row to give Los Angeles a 91-74 lead with 5:33 remaining. Late in the third quarter, O'Neal had the crowd enthralled when he dribbled most of the court and went to the basket only to put up a shot that was one of his few misses. "That was the quickest I've seen him. We had no answer for him,'' Toronto coach Lenny Wilkens said. "A couple of times we couldn't even get there to double-team him. He was so quick, he just turned and shot it. He just had a tremendous game. He was incredible.'' O'Neal had 10 rebounds, one more than Bryant, and made seven of 10 free throws. The Lakers dominated the boards 44-29. Bryant fell one rebound short of a triple-double. "The difference was Shaquille O'Neal,'' Raptors guard Alvin Williams said. "He set the tempo early on and dominated the game. They got a good lead in the first half and we just couldn't catch up. He was just making shots and making foul shots, so it was just a tough night for us.'' Los Angeles still couldn't cut down on its turnovers, committing 17 to go with 19 against Denver on Saturday. But the Lakers shared the ball with 28 assists, and Jackson used all 11 available players. Rookie Kareem Rush had seven points in 26 minutes and Rick Fox had 15 points. While O'Neal was so effective from the field and at the line, Bryant struggled on 5-of-15 shooting. He had no points in the second quarter, then scored seven straight in the third when the Raptors briefly cut their deficit to single digits before the Lakers clamped down. The Lakers initially pulled away in the second quarter on O'Neal's 6-of-8 shooting. They built a 21-point lead with a 22-9 run to open the period, with O'Neal accounting for 11 points. The Raptors cut their deficit to 58-44 at the break by outscoring the Lakers 15-8 to close the half. The Raptors are 0-6 against the Pacific Division this season, including an overtime loss to the Lakers a week ago in Toronto. It hasn't helped that they are decimated by injuries, most notably Vince Carter's strained right knee that has kept him out of the last 10 games. Eric Montross and Lamond Murray are on the injured list. Besides Carter, Toronto center Mamadou N'diaye didn't make the trip because of a stress fracture in his right heel, and starter Antonio Davis was missing due to a swollen right knee.

Game notes
Wilkens said he doesn't know when Carter might return. "I'm hoping that when we get off this road trip that he's feeling better, that maybe there's some progress made with his rehabilitation. He'll know when he can go,'' Wilkens said. ... Lakers F Samaki Walker missed his second straight game because of severe tonsillitis. "He's supposedly contagious, so we have to watch that,'' Jackson said. ... Jackson said he's not talking to Bryant as much about the offense and letting Bryant do his thing. "He's had a tremendous challenge. I'm making him do a lot more than maybe he's capable of doing inside the offense, which is to organize the offense, to get it efficiently to run, to break down pressure a lot of times,'' he said. "He's having a hard time accomplishing that every night.'' Jackson said not even Michael Jordan had to run the offense for the Chicago Bulls. "I can't fault Kobe for a lot of things. I've asked him to be more aggressive on the offensive end on top of it. He'll find his way back inside the offense as the season goes on. He knows what I want,'' Jackson said.
